# .gitattributes — control line endings and diff behavior for cross-platform
# development (Windows + Linux VM). The repo is edited on Windows and built on
# `skyadmin@192.168.13.69` (Linux). Without this, `scp` from Windows lands
# files with CRLF in the repo and they stay CRLF forever.
#
# Strategy: `* text=auto` lets git auto-detect per file; explicit `eol=lf`
# pins LF for files that must be LF to run on Linux (shell scripts, Makefile,
# Python entry points, Go source).
#
# Existing CRLF files in the repo (23) are NOT renormalized in the same
# commit. Re-normalize them later with `git add --renormalize .` as a
# separate, single-purpose PR.

# Default: auto-detect text/binary, normalize to LF on checkout.
* text=auto

# Build / deploy scripts — must be LF on Linux.
Makefile              text eol=lf
*.sh                  text eol=lf
*.mk                  text eol=lf

# Python and Go source — LF.
*.py                  text eol=lf
*.go                  text eol=lf

# Shell scripts that live under deploy/ and scripts/ are covered by the
# `*.sh` rule above; explicit paths kept as documentation:
/deploy/*.sh          text eol=lf
/scripts/*.sh         text eol=lf

# Markdown and YAML are fine with CRLF, but pinning LF avoids noisy diffs
# from accidental editor saves on Windows.
*.md                  text eol=lf
*.yml                 text eol=lf
*.yaml                text eol=lf

# Binary — never touch.
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif binary
*.ico binary
*.pdf binary
*.zip binary
*.gz binary
*.tgz binary
*.tar binary
*.db binary
*.db-wal binary
*.db-shm binary
*.so binary
*.dll binary
*.exe binary
